# language: en
Feature: Public MCP API Surface (Strictly Read-Only)

  As an AI agent or developer using MCP clients (Claude, VS Code Copilot, etc.)
  I want to discover and call a rich set of read-only tools against RisingWave
  So that I can safely inspect, monitor, and analyze the streaming database without any risk of modification

  Background:
    Given the RisingWave MCP Server is running in read-only mode
    And it is connected to a healthy RisingWave instance
    And the server exposes tools via stdio or Streamable HTTP transport

  # ============================================================
  # Tool Discovery
  # ============================================================
  Scenario: Agent discovers all available read-only tools
    When the MCP client requests the list of tools
    Then the server returns a list of tools
    And every tool has a clear name, description, and input schema
    And no tool has any mutating capability (all declare ReadOnlyHint = true)
    And the list includes at minimum:
      | category                  | example tools                          |
      | Query & Generic Executor  | run_select_query, execute_safe_read_query |
      | Explain                   | explain_query, explain_analyze         |
      | Schema                    | show_tables, describe_table, list_materialized_views |
      | Streaming Monitoring      | list_streaming_jobs, get_backfill_progress |
      | Storage                   | get_hummock_stats, list_compaction     |
      | Cluster & Management      | get_cluster_info, get_version          |
    And the powerful generic tool "execute_safe_read_query" is present with rich description of its safeguards

  # ============================================================
  # Safe Query Execution
  # ============================================================
  Scenario: Agent executes a simple safe SELECT query via dedicated tool
    Given a table "orders" exists with sample data
    When the agent calls "run_select_query" with query "SELECT * FROM orders LIMIT 10"
    Then the tool succeeds
    And returns results as structured data or JSON
    And the response includes execution metadata (rows returned, duration)
    And the query was executed using a pooled connection with timeout

  Scenario: Agent uses the powerful generic safe read-only executor
    When the agent calls "execute_safe_read_query" with a complex analytical query
    Then the query is validated through all safety layers
    And if valid, it executes successfully
    And the result includes timing breakdown if observability is enabled
    And the full query (or hash) is logged for audit

  Scenario Outline: Generic executor rejects dangerous or invalid queries
    When the agent calls "execute_safe_read_query" with query "<query>"
    Then the tool rejects the request with a clear, actionable error
    And the rejection reason indicates which safety layer caught it
    And no query is sent to RisingWave
    And the rejection is logged with context

    Examples:
      | query                                      | expected rejection reason      |
      | INSERT INTO orders VALUES (1)              | Mutation keyword detected      |
      | DROP TABLE orders                          | Mutation keyword detected      |
      | CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW ...               | Mutation keyword detected      |
      | SELECT * FROM orders; DROP TABLE users     | Multiple statements or dangerous pattern |
      | UPDATE orders SET amount = 0               | Mutation keyword detected      |
      | DELETE FROM orders                         | Mutation keyword detected      |
      | GRANT ALL ON orders TO public              | Mutation keyword detected      |
      | SELECT pg_sleep(100)                       | Resource limit or unsafe function |

  # ============================================================
  # Schema & Introspection Tools
  # ============================================================
  Scenario: Agent inspects schema and metadata safely
    When the agent calls schema tools (show_tables, describe_table, list_materialized_views, etc.)
    Then all calls succeed
    And return accurate current state from RisingWave catalog
    And no side effects occur on the database

  # ============================================================
  # Monitoring & Observability Tools
  # ============================================================
  Scenario: Agent monitors streaming jobs and storage
    When the agent calls monitoring tools (list_streaming_jobs, get_backfill_progress, get_hummock_stats)
    Then the tools return live information from RisingWave
    And the data helps the agent understand system health without any modification risk

  # ============================================================
  # Error Handling & Agent Experience
  # ============================================================
  Scenario: Agent receives helpful errors for invalid inputs
    When the agent calls a tool with invalid parameters
    Then the server returns a clear, structured error
    And the error message helps the agent correct its request
    And the error is classified (validation, execution, timeout, etc.)

  Scenario: Agent experiences consistent behavior across transports
    Given the server is running
    When the same tool is called via stdio and via Streamable HTTP
    Then both calls produce equivalent successful or error results
    And latency characteristics are documented per transport

  # ============================================================
  # Concurrency from Agent Perspective
  # ============================================================
  Scenario: Multiple agents interact concurrently without interference
    Given 200 concurrent MCP sessions are active
    When many agents call read-only tools simultaneously
    Then all calls complete successfully or with appropriate errors
    And no session can affect another
    And the server maintains stability and low latency

  # ============================================================
  # No Mutation Invariant (Public API)
  # ============================================================
  Scenario: It is impossible to mutate data or schema through any public tool
    When any agent attempts any write operation through any tool or the generic executor
    Then every attempt is rejected at the earliest possible layer
    And the database state remains unchanged
    And the rejection is clearly communicated and logged
    And this holds true even under high concurrency or error conditions